FooUtils.Class.html.title: FooUtils.Class
FooUtils.Class.html.name: Class
FooUtils.Class.html.summary: A base class providing some helper methods for prototypal inheritance.
FooUtils.Class.html.description: This is a base class for making prototypal inheritance simpler to work with. It provides an easy way to inherit from another class and exposes a _super method within the scope of any overriding methods that allows a simple way to execute the overridden function. Have a look at the extend and override method examples to see some basic usage.

FooUtils.animation.html#.end.name: end
FooUtils.animation.html#.end.summary: The animationend event name for the current browser.
FooUtils.animation.html#.end.description: Depending on the browser this returns one of the following values: `"animationend"``"webkitAnimationEnd"``"msAnimationEnd"``"oAnimationEnd"``null` - If the browser doesn't support animations

FooUtils.animation.html#.requestFrame.name: requestFrame
FooUtils.animation.html#.requestFrame.summary: A cross browser wrapper for the requestAnimationFrame method.

FooUtils.animation.html#.duration.name: duration
FooUtils.animation.html#.duration.summary: Gets the animation-duration value for the supplied jQuery element.

FooUtils.animation.html#.iterations.title: <static> iterations( $element [, def ] ) → {number}
FooUtils.animation.html#.iterations.name: iterations
FooUtils.animation.html#.iterations.summary: Gets the animation-iteration-count value for the supplied jQuery element.

FooUtils.animation.html#.start.title: <static> start( $element, classNameOrFunc [, state [, timeout ] ] ) → {Promise}
FooUtils.animation.html#.start.name: start
FooUtils.animation.html#.start.summary: Start a animation by toggling the supplied className on the $element.
FooUtils.animation.html#.start.description: This method lets us use CSS animations by toggling a class and using the animationend event to perform additional actions once the animation has completed across all browsers. In browsers that do not support animations this method would behave the same as if just calling jQuery's .toggleClass method. The last parameter timeout is used to create a timer that behaves as a safety net in case the animationend event is never raised and ensures the deferred returned by this method is resolved or rejected within a specified time. If no timeout is supplied the animation-duration and animation-iterations-count must be set on the $element before this method is called so one can be generated.

FooUtils.animation.html#~startCallback.title: startCallback( $element )
FooUtils.animation.html#~startCallback.name: startCallback
FooUtils.animation.html#~startCallback.summary: The callback function to execute when starting a animation.

FooUtils.fn.html#.CONTAINS_SUPER.title: <static, readonly> CONTAINS_SUPER :RegExp
FooUtils.fn.html#.CONTAINS_SUPER.name: CONTAINS_SUPER
FooUtils.fn.html#.CONTAINS_SUPER.summary: The regular expression to test if a function uses the this._super method applied by the FooUtils.fn.add method.
FooUtils.fn.html#.CONTAINS_SUPER.description: When the script is first loaded into the page this performs a quick check to see if the browser supports function decompilation. If it does the regular expression is set to match the expected _super, however if function decompilation is not supported, the regular expression is set to match anything effectively making the test always return true.

FooUtils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.title: <static> addOrOverride( proto, name, fn )
FooUtils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.name: addOrOverride
FooUtils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.summary: Adds or overrides the given method name on the proto using the supplied fn.
FooUtils.fn.html#.addOrOverride.description: If the new method overrides a pre-existing one, this function will expose the overridden method as this._super within the new methods scope. This replaces having to write out the following to override a method and call its original: var original = MyClass.prototype.someMethod; MyClass.prototype.someMethod = function(arg1, arg2){ // execute the original original.call(this, arg1, arg2); }; With the following: FooUtils.fn.addOrOverride( MyClass.prototype, "someMethod", function(arg1, arg2){ // execute the original this._super(arg1, arg2); }); This method is used by the FooUtils.Class to implement the inheritance of individual methods.

FooUtils.fn.html#.apply.title: <static> apply( klass [, args ] ) → {Object}
FooUtils.fn.html#.apply.name: apply
FooUtils.fn.html#.apply.summary: Use the Function.prototype.apply method on a class constructor using the new keyword.
FooUtils.fn.html#.apply.description: When using the default Function.prototype.apply you can't use it on class constructors requiring the new keyword, this method allows us to do that.

FooUtils.fn.html#.arg2arr.title: <static> arg2arr( args ) → {Array}
FooUtils.fn.html#.arg2arr.name: arg2arr
FooUtils.fn.html#.arg2arr.summary: Converts the default arguments object into a proper array.
FooUtils.fn.html#.arg2arr.description: This method is simply a replacement for calling Array.prototype.slice.call() to create an array from an arguments object.

FooUtils.fn.html#.debounce.title: <static> debounce( fn, time ) → {function}
FooUtils.fn.html#.debounce.name: debounce
FooUtils.fn.html#.debounce.summary: Debounces the fn by the supplied time.
FooUtils.fn.html#.debounce.description: This returns a wrapped version of the fn which delays its' execution by the supplied time. Additional calls to the function will extend the delay until the time expires.

FooUtils.fn.html#.throttle.title: <static> throttle( fn, time ) → {function}
FooUtils.fn.html#.throttle.name: throttle
FooUtils.fn.html#.throttle.summary: Throttles the fn by the supplied time.
FooUtils.fn.html#.throttle.description: This returns a wrapped version of the fn which ensures it's executed only once every time milliseconds. The first call to the function will be executed, after that only the last of any additional calls will be executed once the time expires.

FooUtils.fn.html#.check.title: <static> check( thisArg, value [, def [, ctx ] ] ) → {function}
FooUtils.fn.html#.check.name: check
FooUtils.fn.html#.check.summary: Checks the given value and ensures a function is returned.
FooUtils.fn.html#.check.description: This function is primarily used to check the value of a callback option that could be supplied as either a function or a string. When just the function name is supplied this method uses the FooUtils.fn.fetch method to resolve and wrap it to ensure when it's called the correct context is applied. Being able to resolve a function from a name allows callbacks to be easily set even through data attributes as you can just supply the full function name as a string and then use this method to retrieve the actual function.

FooUtils.fn.html#.fetch.title: <static> fetch( name [, ctx ] ) → {function}
FooUtils.fn.html#.fetch.name: fetch
FooUtils.fn.html#.fetch.summary: Fetches a function given its name.

FooUtils.fn.html#.enqueue.title: <static> enqueue( objects, name [, arg1 [, ...argN ] ] ) → {Promise}
FooUtils.fn.html#.enqueue.name: enqueue
FooUtils.fn.html#.enqueue.summary: Enqueues methods using the given name from all supplied objects and executes each in order with the given arguments.
FooUtils.fn.html#.enqueue.description: This method allows an array of objects that implement a common set of methods to be executed in a supplied order. Each method in the queue is only executed after the successful completion of the previous. Success is evaluated as the method did not throw an error and if it returned a promise it was resolved. An example of this being used within the plugin is the loading and execution of methods on the various components. Using this method ensures components are loaded and have their methods executed in a static order regardless of when they were registered with the plugin or if the method is async. This way if ComponentB's preinit relies on properties set in ComponentA's preinit method you can register ComponentB with a lower priority than ComponentA and you can be assured ComponentA's preinit completed successfully before ComponentB's preinit is called event if it performs an async operation.

FooUtils.fn.html#.when.title: <static> when( promises ) → {Promise}
FooUtils.fn.html#.when.name: when
FooUtils.fn.html#.when.summary: Waits for the outcome of all promises regardless of failure and resolves supplying the results of just those that succeeded.

FooUtils.fn.html#.rejectWith.name: rejectWith
FooUtils.fn.html#.rejectWith.summary: Return a promise rejected using the supplied args.

FooUtils.fn.html#.resolveWith.name: resolveWith
FooUtils.fn.html#.resolveWith.summary: Return a promise resolved using the supplied args.

FooUtils.is.html.summary: Contains common type checking utility methods.

FooUtils.is.html#.array.title: <static> array( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.array.name: array
FooUtils.is.html#.array.summary: Checks if the value is an array.

FooUtils.is.html#.boolean.title: <static> boolean( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.boolean.name: boolean
FooUtils.is.html#.boolean.summary: Checks if the value is a boolean.

FooUtils.is.html#.element.title: <static> element( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.element.name: element
FooUtils.is.html#.element.summary: Checks if the value is an element.

FooUtils.is.html#.empty.title: <static> empty( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.empty.name: empty
FooUtils.is.html#.empty.summary: Checks if the value is empty.
FooUtils.is.html#.empty.description: The following values are considered to be empty by this method: `""` - An empty string`0` - 0 as an integer`0.0` - 0 as a float`[]` - An empty array`{}` - An empty object`$()` - An empty jQuery object`false``null``undefined`

FooUtils.is.html#.error.title: <static> error( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.error.name: error
FooUtils.is.html#.error.summary: Checks if the value is an error.

FooUtils.is.html#.fn.title: <static> fn( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.fn.name: fn
FooUtils.is.html#.fn.summary: Checks if the value is a function.

FooUtils.is.html#.hash.title: <static> hash( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.hash.name: hash
FooUtils.is.html#.hash.summary: Checks if the value is a hash.

FooUtils.is.html#.jq.title: <static> jq( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.jq.name: jq
FooUtils.is.html#.jq.summary: Checks if the value is a jQuery object.

FooUtils.is.html#.number.title: <static> number( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.number.name: number
FooUtils.is.html#.number.summary: Checks if the value is a number.

FooUtils.is.html#.object.title: <static> object( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.object.name: object
FooUtils.is.html#.object.summary: Checks if the value is an object.

FooUtils.is.html#.promise.title: <static> promise( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.promise.name: promise
FooUtils.is.html#.promise.summary: Checks if the value is a promise.
FooUtils.is.html#.promise.description: This is a simple check to determine if an object is a jQuery promise object. It simply checks the object has a then and promise function defined. The promise object is created as an object literal inside of jQuery.Deferred, it has no prototype, nor any other truly unique properties that could be used to distinguish it. This method should be a little more accurate than the internal jQuery one that simply checks for a promise function.

FooUtils.is.html#.size.title: <static> size( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.size.name: size
FooUtils.is.html#.size.summary: Checks if the value is a valid CSS length.

FooUtils.is.html#.string.title: <static> string( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.string.name: string
FooUtils.is.html#.string.summary: Checks if the value is a string.

FooUtils.is.html#.undef.title: <static> undef( value ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.is.html#.undef.name: undef
FooUtils.is.html#.undef.summary: Checks if the value is undefined.

FooUtils.obj.html#.create.title: <static> create( proto ) → {Object}
FooUtils.obj.html#.create.name: create
FooUtils.obj.html#.create.summary: Creates a new object with the specified prototype.
FooUtils.obj.html#.create.description: This is a basic implementation of the Object.create method.

FooUtils.obj.html#.extend.title: <static> extend( target, object [, ...objectN ] ) → {Object}
FooUtils.obj.html#.extend.name: extend
FooUtils.obj.html#.extend.summary: Merge the contents of two or more objects together into the first target object.
FooUtils.obj.html#.extend.description: This does not merge arrays by index as jQuery does, it treats them as a single property and replaces the array with a shallow copy of the new one. This method makes use of the FooUtils.obj.merge method internally.

FooUtils.obj.html#.merge.title: <static> merge( target, object ) → {Object}
FooUtils.obj.html#.merge.name: merge
FooUtils.obj.html#.merge.summary: Merge the contents of two objects together into the first target object.
FooUtils.obj.html#.merge.description: This does not merge arrays by index as jQuery does, it treats them as a single property and replaces the array with a shallow copy of the new one. This method is used internally by the FooUtils.obj.extend method.

FooUtils.obj.html#.mergeValid.title: <static> mergeValid( target, validators, object [, mappings ] ) → {Object}
FooUtils.obj.html#.mergeValid.name: mergeValid
FooUtils.obj.html#.mergeValid.summary: Merge the validated properties of the object into the target using the optional mappings.

FooUtils.obj.html#.prop.title: <static> prop( object, name [, value ] ) → {*}
FooUtils.obj.html#.prop.name: prop
FooUtils.obj.html#.prop.summary: Get or set a property value given its name.

FooUtils.str.html#.camel.title: <static> camel( target ) → {string}
FooUtils.str.html#.camel.name: camel
FooUtils.str.html#.camel.summary: Converts the given target to camel case.

FooUtils.str.html#.kebab.title: <static> kebab( target ) → {string}
FooUtils.str.html#.kebab.name: kebab
FooUtils.str.html#.kebab.summary: Converts the given target to kebab case. Non-alphanumeric characters are converted to -.

FooUtils.str.html#.contains.title: <static> contains( target, substr [, ignoreCase ] ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.str.html#.contains.name: contains
FooUtils.str.html#.contains.summary: Checks if the target contains the given substr.

FooUtils.str.html#.containsWord.title: <static> containsWord( target, word [, ignoreCase ] ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.str.html#.containsWord.name: containsWord
FooUtils.str.html#.containsWord.summary: Checks if the target contains the given word.
FooUtils.str.html#.containsWord.description: This method differs from FooUtils.str.contains in that it searches for whole words by splitting the target string on word boundaries (\b) and then comparing the individual parts.

FooUtils.str.html#.endsWith.title: <static> endsWith( target, substr ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.str.html#.endsWith.name: endsWith
FooUtils.str.html#.endsWith.summary: Checks if the target ends with the given substr.

FooUtils.str.html#.escapeRegExp.title: <static> escapeRegExp( target ) → {string}
FooUtils.str.html#.escapeRegExp.name: escapeRegExp
FooUtils.str.html#.escapeRegExp.summary: Escapes the target for use in a regular expression.

FooUtils.str.html#.fnv1a.title: <static> fnv1a( target ) → {number}
FooUtils.str.html#.fnv1a.name: fnv1a
FooUtils.str.html#.fnv1a.summary: Generates a 32 bit FNV-1a hash from the given target.

FooUtils.str.html#.from.title: <static> from( target, substr ) → {string}
FooUtils.str.html#.from.name: from
FooUtils.str.html#.from.summary: Returns the remainder of the target split on the first index of the given substr.

FooUtils.str.html#.join.title: <static> join( separator, part [, ...partN ] ) → {string}
FooUtils.str.html#.join.name: join
FooUtils.str.html#.join.summary: Joins any number of strings using the given separator.
FooUtils.str.html#.join.description: This method differs from using the standard Array.prototype.join function to join strings in that it ignores empty parts and checks to see if each starts with the supplied separator. If the part starts with the separator it is removed before appending it to the final result.

FooUtils.str.html#.startsWith.title: <static> startsWith( target, substr ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.str.html#.startsWith.name: startsWith
FooUtils.str.html#.startsWith.summary: Checks if the target starts with the given substr.

FooUtils.str.html#.until.title: <static> until( target, substr ) → {string}
FooUtils.str.html#.until.name: until
FooUtils.str.html#.until.summary: Returns the first part of the target split on the first index of the given substr.

FooUtils.str.html#.format.title: <static> format( target, arg1 [, ...argN ] ) → {string}
FooUtils.str.html#.format.name: format
FooUtils.str.html#.format.summary: A basic string formatter that can use both index and name based placeholders but handles only string or number replacements.
FooUtils.str.html#.format.description: This method allows you to supply the replacements as an object when using named placeholders or as an array or additional arguments when using index placeholders. This does not perform a simultaneous replacement of placeholders, which is why it's referred to as a basic formatter. This means replacements that contain placeholders within there value could end up being replaced themselves as seen in the last example.

FooUtils.transition.html.title: FooUtils.transition
FooUtils.transition.html.name: transition
FooUtils.transition.html.summary: Contains common utility methods and members for the CSS transition property.

FooUtils.transition.html#.supported.title: <static> supported :boolean
FooUtils.transition.html#.supported.name: supported
FooUtils.transition.html#.supported.summary: Whether or not transitions are supported by the current browser.

FooUtils.transition.html#.end.title: <static> end :string
FooUtils.transition.html#.end.name: end
FooUtils.transition.html#.end.summary: The transitionend event name for the current browser.
FooUtils.transition.html#.end.description: Depending on the browser this returns one of the following values: `"transitionend"``"webkitTransitionEnd"``"msTransitionEnd"``"oTransitionEnd"``null` - If the browser doesn't support transitions

FooUtils.transition.html#.duration.title: <static> duration( $element [, def ] ) → {number}
FooUtils.transition.html#.duration.name: duration
FooUtils.transition.html#.duration.summary: Gets the transition-duration value for the supplied jQuery element.

FooUtils.transition.html#.start.title: <static> start( $element, classNameOrFunc [, state [, timeout ] ] ) → {Promise}
FooUtils.transition.html#.start.name: start
FooUtils.transition.html#.start.summary: Start a transition by toggling the supplied className on the $element.
FooUtils.transition.html#.start.description: This method lets us use CSS transitions by toggling a class and using the transitionend event to perform additional actions once the transition has completed across all browsers. In browsers that do not support transitions this method would behave the same as if just calling jQuery's .toggleClass method. The last parameter timeout is used to create a timer that behaves as a safety net in case the transitionend event is never raised and ensures the deferred returned by this method is resolved or rejected within a specified time.

FooUtils.transition.html#~startCallback.title: startCallback( $element )
FooUtils.transition.html#~startCallback.name: startCallback
FooUtils.transition.html#~startCallback.summary: The callback function to execute when starting a transition.

FooUtils.url.html#.parts.title: <static> parts( url ) → {FooUtils.url~Parts}
FooUtils.url.html#.parts.name: parts
FooUtils.url.html#.parts.summary: Parses the supplied url into an object containing it's component parts.

FooUtils.url.html#.full.title: <static> full( url ) → {string}
FooUtils.url.html#.full.name: full
FooUtils.url.html#.full.summary: Given a url that could be relative or full this ensures a full url is returned.
FooUtils.url.html#.full.description: Given a full url this will simply return it however if given a relative url this will create a full url using the current location to fill in the blanks.

FooUtils.url.html#.param.title: <static> param( search, key [, value ] ) → {string}
FooUtils.url.html#.param.name: param
FooUtils.url.html#.param.summary: Gets or sets a parameter in the given search string.

FooUtils.html.title: FooUtils
FooUtils.html.name: FooUtils
FooUtils.html.summary: This namespace contains common utility methods and code shared between our plugins.
FooUtils.html.description: This namespace relies on jQuery being included in the page prior to it being loaded.

FooUtils.html#.$.title: <static> $ :jQuery
FooUtils.html#.$.summary: A reference to the jQuery object the library is registered with.
FooUtils.html#.$.description: This is used internally for all jQuery operations to help work around issues where multiple jQuery libraries have been included in a single page.

FooUtils.html#.ready.title: <static> ready( callback )
FooUtils.html#.ready.name: ready
FooUtils.html#.ready.summary: Waits for the DOM to be accessible and then executes the supplied callback.

FooUtils.html#.find.title: <static> find( target, callback [, thisArg ] ) → {*}
FooUtils.html#.find.name: find
FooUtils.html#.find.summary: Returns the value of the first element or property in the provided target that satisfies the provided test function.

FooUtils.html#.each.title: <static> each( object, callback [, thisArg ] )
FooUtils.html#.each.name: each
FooUtils.html#.each.summary: Iterate over all indexes or properties of the provided target executing the provided callback once per value.

FooUtils.html#.getViewportBounds.title: <static> getViewportBounds( [ inflate ] ) → {FooUtils.Bounds}
FooUtils.html#.getViewportBounds.name: getViewportBounds
FooUtils.html#.getViewportBounds.summary: Gets the bounding rectangle of the current viewport.

FooUtils.html#.versionCompare.title: <static> versionCompare( version1, version2 ) → {number}
FooUtils.html#.versionCompare.name: versionCompare
FooUtils.html#.versionCompare.description: This method will compare two version numbers that conform to the basic MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH format returning the result as a simple number. This method will handle short version string comparisons e.g. 1.0 versus 1.0.1.

FooUtils.html#.getElementBounds.title: <static> getElementBounds( element ) → {FooUtils.Bounds}
FooUtils.html#.getElementBounds.name: getElementBounds
FooUtils.html#.getElementBounds.summary: Get the bounding rectangle for the supplied element.

FooUtils.html#.uniqueId.title: <static> uniqueId( $element [, prefix ] ) → {string}
FooUtils.html#.uniqueId.name: uniqueId
FooUtils.html#.uniqueId.summary: Generate and apply a unique id for the given $element.

FooUtils.html#.removeUniqueId.title: <static> removeUniqueId( $element )
FooUtils.html#.removeUniqueId.name: removeUniqueId
FooUtils.html#.removeUniqueId.summary: Remove the id from the given $element if it was set using the uniqueId method.

FooUtils.html#.selectify.title: <static> selectify( classes ) → {object|string}
FooUtils.html#.selectify.name: selectify
FooUtils.html#.selectify.summary: Convert CSS class names into CSS selectors.

FooUtils.html#.src.title: <static> src( src, srcset, srcWidth, srcHeight, renderWidth, renderHeight [, devicePixelRatio ] ) → {string|null}
FooUtils.html#.src.name: src
FooUtils.html#.src.summary: Parses the supplied src and srcset values and returns the best matching URL for the supplied render size.
FooUtils.html#.src.description: This can be used to parse the correct src to use when loading an image through JavaScript.

FooUtils.html#.scrollParent.title: <static> scrollParent( element [, axis [, def ] ] ) → {jQuery}
FooUtils.html#.scrollParent.name: scrollParent
FooUtils.html#.scrollParent.summary: Get the scroll parent for the supplied element optionally filtering by axis.

FooUtils.html#~readyCallback.title: readyCallback( $ )
FooUtils.html#~readyCallback.name: readyCallback
FooUtils.html#~readyCallback.summary: The callback for the FooUtils.ready method.

FooUtils.html#~findCallback.title: findCallback( value [, key [, object ] ] ) → {boolean}
FooUtils.html#~findCallback.name: findCallback
FooUtils.html#~findCallback.summary: Executed once for each array index or object property until it returns a truthy value.

FooUtils.html#~eachCallback.title: eachCallback( value [, key [, object ] ] ) → {boolean|void}
FooUtils.html#~eachCallback.name: eachCallback
FooUtils.html#~eachCallback.summary: Executed once for each array index or object property.
